<paragraph id="B3DA11AC1843A41BEA8F4BFF5FE674EF" pageNumber="32">
Key to the species of 
<taxonomicName id="D6D81711E64DB84232D7F582B00B61FC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B642B859C04F29F34B90EB14BEBBED67" type="key">
<paragraph id="239C56AC15A98B976D745234BF1665C9" pageNumber="32">
1. (a) More than 50 spots in the caudal fin, anterior projection on the lateral ethmoid (Fig. 8), ventral flange on the anterior process of the interopercle, tooth patch of infrapharyngobranchial # 5 covers only the dorsal region of that bone, width of the lateral ethmoid at the joint with infraorbital 1+2 (io 1+2) very narrow (as much as 3/4 narrower than the width of the lateral ethmoid in 
<taxonomicName id="C334F518B5DA9C6CD01F042C67D9FC1B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4F56A018954E4EB145E050BEC06C6DB3" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="45EB06B3AFE804B79C6C10EC8E296B9D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8590D22ADE3F61B7E79936D1D6CDBC3A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="9F258938B28D4B881AFC47902D255441" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="corruscans">P. corruscans</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E0CA0BF3B257FA2097876C53BCEBE40C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="magdaleniatum">P. magdaleniatum</taxonomicName>
..............................2
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F52F52F81BF31EF921407644ADC9637" pageNumber="32">(b) Fewer than 45 spots in the caudal fin, no anterior projection on the lateral ethmoid, absence of ventral flange on the anterior process of the interopercle, tooth patch of infrapharyngobranchial # 5 covers dorsal and extends over 2/3 of ventral region of that bone, wide lateral ethmoid at the joint with infraorbital 1+2 (io 1+2)............................................................................3</paragraph>
<paragraph id="832B6E80D595060B77E8FA569DF8FC9F" pageNumber="32">
2. (a) Dark loops or reticulated bars along the side of the body (Fig. 15), no spots on the lateral region of the body............................................. 
<taxonomicName id="DDB843D34117BF32B6260A43070268A3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
(Amazon River and tributaries).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C24438E3464C49D893B0F1AFB2A2BCC" pageNumber="32">
(b) Dark vertical bars and few spots (no more than 10) randomly distributed along the side of the body. .................... 
<taxonomicName id="AC9F3852C0A3A3A9B938DB0BF6F47DB9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="metaense">P. metaense</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="AB1D0946F6E39356682706FD1E490468" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Orinoco River and tributaries in Colombia and Venezuela).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A7CCE01F6AA1095574D111C4EC73BD4" pageNumber="32">
3. (a) Nuchal plate # 1 expanded, posterior region of the metapterygoid wider than in the other species... ........... 
<taxonomicName id="0F23E2F90135706F48677A7D993939DE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="magdaleniatum">P. magdaleniatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="70194B99267984FD5FD3D0CF574F8B94" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Magdalena and Cauca rivers, north-central region of Colombia).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="738AEED860C5B233ACB5D12C528128C7" pageNumber="32">(b) Nuchal plate # 1 reduced and not expanded.............................................4</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DBC27B71342D0F843C0910F1B12ABAF6" pageNumber="32">
4. (a) Thick loop-like or reticulated bars on the side of the body, dark loop-like bars join those in the dorsal region of the body forming distinct cells, dorsal region of head has either loops or spots............. ................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="899E00AC269473575BB1D9B09ED8B48A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
(Amazon and 
<normalizedToken id="796C88B6A57C854AF26C253BE4CBF56D" originalValue="Paraná">Parana</normalizedToken>
rivers)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FF4841952E80345611CEE6B8E7AFF9EE" pageNumber="32">(b) No loop-like bars on the side of the body; spots or pale vertical bars common and located close to the dark vertical bars....................................................................5</paragraph>
<paragraph id="07E101A8CF812DBD271F0DD1BF82D0FE" pageNumber="32">
5. (a) Spots distributed regularly in six to eight rows from the posterior margin of the opercle to the tail... 
<taxonomicName id="62BC34C1539031CD7039F0F75EB756BC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="corruscans">P. corruscans</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="5AE77ED0B182637B99550BB7FD86705A" originalValue="Paraná">Parana</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken id="2320A125913EEFCFA8C83E213E714652" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco rivers, in Argentina, Paraguay, Uruguay and southeast Brazil).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DA6F6F3FFCBDAA269DBDFA4CC102B9F4" pageNumber="32">(b) Straight dark vertical bars along the side of the body.....................................6</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E38E03991C07A4566DD0CE217B49341" lastPageNumber="33" pageNumber="32">
6. (a) Well-defined straight dark vertical bars on the side of the body, longer than those in 
<taxonomicName id="DEBC89C3C934B94215EAEDC8561B2421" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="AB1011B22953DA447555C5D7AC375DE6" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
, vertical bars of the anterior region also straight and extending below the dorsolateral dusky area, bars do not form spots as seen on other species, usually no spots below lateral line, some individuals 
<pageStartToken id="698A63257771FC0F64BE96AEC3FE962D" pageNumber="33">have</pageStartToken>
two or three spots ................................................................ ............... 
<taxonomicName id="51A2B43B3E83406AA172318DD61D7806" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="32" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="BC40A9603F55065DDFD4EA50AAE7DE7A" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Orinoco River, and its tributaries in Colombia and Venezuela).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DF87232E9F7864375AC23376FC7E9562" pageNumber="33">(b) Dark vertical bars form spots below the lateral line, well -defined pale vertical bars, distinct demarcated boundary between the dusky dorsolateral and pale ventrolateral regions of the body ............... 7</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4B1183DEEBE17E703DE99040EF2B3D93" pageNumber="33">
7. (a) First spinelet of the anal fin contacts the haemal arch of the 24th vertebra, some specimens have spots below the laterodorsal dark region, 43-45 vertebrae .......................................... ...................................... 
<taxonomicName id="299B7951443E9863900C89E494EFD15A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
(Rupununi, Essequibo and Suriname rivers).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D2C98AE43FFFBD1824794D0B144864E" pageNumber="33">
(b) First spinelet of the anal fin contacts the haemal arch of the 22nd vertebra, 37-40 vertebrae, free discrete dark spots below the laterodorsal dark region (Fig. 15), adipose fin with fewer (6 or 8) spots than on 
<taxonomicName id="4AA9588E7E0F1440493813063211097D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
...................................... 
<taxonomicName id="29E436C3A04B5B2CE52EE08812D952E0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
(Amazon River and tributaries).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6F1816AD939FF20D7E3A16DE9F168D2D" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="02DC25292DE1072C3940F4A448CCCEF9" pageNumber="33">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD8ECF0E4A616254AAFA163D884EA230" pageNumber="33">
Unrecognized species of 
<taxonomicName id="9B2B97435E23B64F4DEA6C8B7A3C96DF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
have been included under the names 
<taxonomicName id="DCA1D965DCD99440A0439EBF30AF5E51" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5B8EC60203851DC7CECBC448EC992B86" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
for decades. Considering the wide distribution of both species, at least as regarded in the current literature, this classification results in an underestimation of diversity. Comparative analysis of the morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="957E256FDDDDD2FE11A7A3C1B45F55F5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="338DAE229B55194D2024E408FCA47BAB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
throughout their ranges supports the prediction that each major river basin of the region (e.g., Guyanas) represents a different species. Thus, the 
<taxonomicName id="1392FBB288E7580E606DDC5B58439FB8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="17A673604489C803B83DF091648301F1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
clades represent six and two different species, respectively. This brings the total number of species recognized in 
<taxonomicName id="4136A334FF5A52A4237AA660667FAD07" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
to eight. Two species (
<taxonomicName id="DC78E8B8E3841E4475D0E0BE4EC1F7F4" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C15A6C36F2CDA400EC38EE51180C77B7" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
) are sympatric in the Amazon Basin, two (
<taxonomicName id="EEE9BD9DF2E46C8A737557F6B6621E69" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="metaense">P. metaense</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="06299FEB3C57D0C6C8869C5A0B3884A2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
) are sympatric in the Orinoco Basin, and two others, 
<taxonomicName id="6959D03481495B3CD80B45A993E39A37" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="corruscans">P. corruscans</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="04BAD536E0D5A75A019E064DC7353B42" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
, are sympatric in the 
<normalizedToken id="05C0248BDC23DB912421C9C8574D668E" originalValue="Paraná">Parana</normalizedToken>
. 
<taxonomicName id="05B82A6302391B3B97FEE69ACCA21246" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="magdaleniatum">Pseudoplatystoma magdaleniatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6CE300D967778D647C5FDE412F39DC04" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
each occur as the only species of 
<taxonomicName id="1309E3DD3DCFD55AFC565849B3151130" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
in their respective individual ranges. 
<taxonomicName id="6277AEB022AC1A1470F645769CDBCCAF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">Pseudoplatystoma reticulatum</taxonomicName>
may be sympatric with the two other species in the Amazon Basin, but we have no records of them being captured together in the mainstem or tributaries. Herein we restrict 
<taxonomicName id="827BEFF1F78CF975856D57F8D3A526EF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
to the Essequibo, Rupununi and Suriname rivers. Whether 
<taxonomicName id="4E4D61405A550457C2013DBBD510B53E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
, as envisioned here, was fractured as a result of vicariance events is difficult to test because the Guyanan Shield antedates the formation of the major river basins in northern South America (see Lundberg et al., 2000). Dispersion, the other alternative, requires interconnections between Guyana -Amazonian as well as Guyana -Orinocoan rivers. Indeed, connections do exist among some of the rivers, i.e., Branco -Essequibo rivers (Guyana region) and some lowland interconnections in the state of Para (Brazil) that may have allowed Amazonian -Guyanan transfers (J. G. Lundberg, pers. comm.). Whether transfers occurred or still exist at the present time is not known. 
<taxonomicName id="1D6ECF7C1254A074231049CD0075D579" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum</taxonomicName>
may have evolved after dispersion from the Amazon River and in isolation during the last glaciation in the Pleistocene (2 Mya.). 
<taxonomicName id="A27DC08806FA6D1AA0F879CD6E618311" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">Pseudoplatystoma orinocoense</taxonomicName>
, a species described here as new, resembles 
<taxonomicName id="657D63B0954587BECDFA047AC93AB260" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9E8F999758E34D57EF11DE4DDC156F56" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
. The color pattern and anatomy characters are somewhat similar in these three species and they form a clade within 
<taxonomicName id="762620C6BE04759834BBE12ECCCB3C75" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
([
<taxonomicName id="EFA533C3F0E2A4F3F8B3843836356F24" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName id="037A25C00000D27A25A7509397A68659" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
] + [
<taxonomicName id="ADA6CAE246191E912DD98065CE96B891" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
] Buitrago - 
<normalizedToken id="F5C0B91870C4F76F35BD74CC8F7E361F" originalValue="Suárez">Suarez</normalizedToken>
, 2005). The Amazon and Orinoco rivers are connected by the Casiquiare Canal; hence, fish species interchanges between these two basins are certainly possible. Furthermore, life history studies on 
<taxonomicName id="3565AE86B8CDA8765780EFFC12E9DCCF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2223AA86213EB167249240656BC059DE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
(Orinoco River basin) suggest that these two species make short migrations (Escobar et al., in prep.). Armbruster and Provenzano (2000) suggested that the Casiquiare canal has a recent origin. This suggestion coupled with observations of Escobar et al. (op. cit.) allows for a prediction that species of 
<taxonomicName id="5FD08638D225825BCA10C9F13BBEF744" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
may have been isolated from one another for a much greater time period than previously thought. The same situation applies to 
<taxonomicName id="A05D19B1E405799A7D3A9A56BB239152" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
because it has been traditionally considered a widely distributed species throughout the Amazon and Orinoco rivers (Ringuelet et al., 1967; Mees, 1974; Schultz, 1944; Burgess, 1989), and has been confused with 
<taxonomicName id="96163AAE30FE404814C5F57E489271A6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
(see below PCA).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3D5D21ED00A9E2DBF43306FBF62D0C72" lastPageNumber="34" pageNumber="33">
PCA showed complete separation of 
<taxonomicName id="42D20408A3AC4272AE18259CC8D8DD15" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="magdaleniatum">P. magdaleniatum</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="8AF4EAF553FABBF50250560A9EBFDF0B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orinocoense">P. orinocoense</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 28A). PCA also showed 
<pageStartToken id="20341D0AEECD22121D2FF980F2036031" pageNumber="34">an</pageStartToken>
almost complete separation of 
<taxonomicName id="0C7E9EA45D5367053CA0D592ECA1295A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="magdaleniatum">P. magdaleniatum</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="E3309B55C10C933F203EE20F828E3A3B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
, but no separation between that species and 
<taxonomicName id="008DC3AFB8E2E5D4E95A89F1870695A8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="puntifer">P. puntifer</taxonomicName>
. PC2 is most strongly and negatively affected by the dorsal fin base length and anal fin base length, and positively affected by the maxillary barbel length and the anterior chin barbel length.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C3A0ECA153ED3BC94FF94C60F20CDB28">
<paragraph id="47917D6186F31B2F51C7EAD1CB1FAADE" pageNumber="34">
FIGURE 28. Principal component analyses of the species of 
<taxonomicName id="617478F73998FF13BFFA912F6E2A10C0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
with similar pigmentation patterns. A, species with dark vertical bars; and B, species with loops.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E7843050403EC144512CA5211F9C7427" pageNumber="36">
<pageStartToken id="86DBE9ECD7A33EEB1C2A295B24BFC8B5" pageNumber="36">PCA</pageStartToken>
showed complete separation of 
<taxonomicName id="AC940C1D772A94FAA0B3E20ED53CFD85" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="476B96DB0EDC9168C32FA75E5AD4E7BE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 28B). PC2 is strongly and negatively affected by the dorsal fin base length and adipose fin length, and positively affected by the distance between the pectoral fin and pelvic fin. Separation of 
<taxonomicName id="66CAFA2B061B364C605692FE1453256B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF7C11A1-A4A8-4292-80C2-8758CB3C5408" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma fasciatum reticulatum Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann 1889:30" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reticulatum">P. reticulatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="FC4C961C90106BC05DD2F5CAD0ADB5B1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:01DF72E1-6947-4D0E-B598-2780D54AFC38" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Platystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Platystoma tigrinum Valenciennes 1840:10" order="Diptera" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tigrinum">P. tigrinum</taxonomicName>
is consistent with differences in morphology. These two species have similar pigmentation pattern represented by dark loops. PC analyses were not informative when 
<taxonomicName id="44B771582ABE3DA25CC9428A57584358" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9D64F3445DDA4223736B5ABDF2D55E9F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctifer">P. punctifer</taxonomicName>
were studied together. These two are presumed sister species and have a similar head and body shape. The same situation was observed when PCA was applied to 
<taxonomicName id="CB1FAEBA0E4C062C9264EA79F26D2373" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="corruscans">P. corruscans</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="F77D8A57FB689C977B4DC063582508EA" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco River) and 
<taxonomicName id="E99FD3573ADCAD3C6D0C4EB727E6D721" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="corruscans">P. corruscans</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="3F72080AC84CA0D0EB2AC2690CD30062" originalValue="Paraná">Parana</normalizedToken>
River).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AC5A66DE7DA9C69E451D5D5249DADAA3" pageNumber="36">
Cuvier and Valenciennes (1840) and Schomburgk (1841) commented on a structure noticed by Schneider on 
<taxonomicName id="82598EF7093B910BC283007A2A77765D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fasciatum">P. fasciatum</taxonomicName>
from Suriname. Schneider (no date) observed a small hole on each side above the pectoral fin by which the abdomen presumably inflated. We did not find such a pore in the material examined, and moreover there is neither an internal organ associated with such a pore nor ducts connected to the skin that might allow any suggestion of the presence of external pores.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0AA3BF63B65B45F59956137168A60FAD" pageNumber="36">
We have seen tiny young of 
<taxonomicName id="72AC81DB1DE3BFE6131035BB3D1656D3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
being marketed in the ornamental fish trade in both North and South America. Individuals were too small for certain identification, but slight pattern and shape differences may indicate that more than one species is being imported. All the species are sold commonly in the numerous open fish markets throughout much of South America. Catch data from the different basins can now be better clarified to include all eight species of 
<taxonomicName id="52A5CE1A13531D1385C267530E7C0D00" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D25A861B-8DAE-4D3E-93DE-9BBB19B28535" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pseudoplatystoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudoplatystoma Bleeker 1862:10" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudoplatystoma</taxonomicName>
, and will allow for more accurate assessment of fishing impact on all the species.
</paragraph>
